    <item>
      <title>Open My Web Site</title>
      <link>https://mkohana.github.io/post/Open-My-Web-Site/</link>
      <pubDate>Fri, 23 Dec 2016 21:11:48 +0900</pubDate>
      
      <guid>https://mkohana.github.io/post/Open-My-Web-Site/</guid>
      <description>

&lt;p&gt;Today I open my web site.
This site is powered by &lt;a href=&#34;https://gohugo.io&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34;&gt;hugo&lt;/a&gt;
and uses &lt;a href=&#34;https://github.com/gcushen/hugo-academic&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34;&gt;academic template&lt;/a&gt;
created by George Cushen.
To host my site, I use github pages. However, I was faced with some problems.
The following is a note for me to host a hugo site on github pages.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h3 id=&#34;repository-structure&#34;&gt;Repository Structure&lt;/h3&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The most web sites or blogs creates two branches, master and gh-pages.
The master branch includes the sources.
Using these source files, hugo builds a web site under the public directory
(that can be changed on config.toml).
The gh-pages branch has the site created by hugo
and it is published on github pages.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;However, personal or organization github pages cannot use gh-pages branch.
On these github pages, the master branch is published as a web site.
Therefore, we need to push the files under the public directory
to the master branch.
So I create master branch and devel branch.
The deploy method follows &lt;a href=&#34;https://gohugo.io/tutorials/github-pages-blog/&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34;&gt;the official document&lt;/a&gt;.
And I replace &amp;ldquo;master&amp;rdquo; with &amp;ldquo;devel&amp;rdquo; and also &amp;ldquo;gh-pages&amp;rdquo; with &amp;ldquo;master&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Finally, I had mistake on the config.toml.
If the &amp;ldquo;/&amp;rdquo; at the last of baseurl, the created link misses the separater.
As the result, the link target becomes &amp;ldquo;github.iopublication&amp;rdquo;, for example.&lt;/p&gt;
</description>
